SIMPLE: just
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Just
<hw>Just</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>juste</ets>, L.
<ets>justus</ets>, fr. <ets>jus</ets> right, law, justice; orig., that
which is fitting; akin to Skr. <ets>yu</ets> to join. Cf.
<er>Injury</er>, <er>Judge</er>, <er>Jury</er>,
<er>Giusto</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Conforming or conformable to rectitude or justice;
not doing wrong to any; violating no right or obligation; upright;
righteous; honest; true; -- said both of persons and things.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧O <xex>just</xex> but severe law!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is not a <qex>just</qex> man upon earth, that doeth good,
and sinneth not.</q> <rj><qau>Eccl. vii. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Just</qex> balances, <qex>just</qex> weights, . . . shall ye
have.</q> <rj><qau>Lev. xix. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How should man be <qex>just</qex> with God?</q> <rj><qau>Job ix.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We know your grace to be a man.⟦br⟧
<qex>Just</qex> and upright.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not transgressing the requirement of truth and
propriety; conformed to the truth of things, to reason, or to a proper
standard; exact; normal; reasonable; regular; due; <as>as, a
<ex>just</ex> statement; a <ex>just</ex> inference.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Just</qex> of thy word, in every thought sincere.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prince is here at hand: pleaseth your lordship⟦br⟧
To meet his grace <qex>just</qex> distance 'tween our armies.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was a comely personage, a little above <qex>just</qex>
stature.</q> <qau>Bacon.</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fire fitted with <qex>just</qex> materials casts a constant
heat.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When all⟦br⟧
The war shall stand ranged in its <qex>just</qex> array.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their names alone would make a <qex>just</qex> volume.</q>
<rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Rendering or disposed to render to each one his due;
equitable; fair; impartial; <as>as, <ex>just</ex> judge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are commonly so <qex>just</qex> to virtue and goodness as to
praise it in others, even when they do not practice it themselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Just intonation</b></col>. <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The correct sounding of notes or intervals; true pitch</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The giving all chords and intervals in their purity or
their exact mathematical ratio, or without <contr>temperament</contr>; a
process in which the number of notes and intervals required in the
various keys is much greater than the twelve to the octave used in
systems of temperament.</cd> <rj><au>H. W. Poole.</au></rj></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Equitable; upright; honest; true; fair;
impartial; proper; exact; normal; orderly; regular.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Just</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Just
<hw>Just</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Precisely; exactly; --
in place, time, or degree; neither more nor less than is
stated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And having <qex>just</qex> enough, not covet more.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The god Pan guided my hand <qex>just</qex> to the heart of the
beast.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To-night, at Herne's oak, <qex>just</qex> 'twixt twelve and
one.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Closely; nearly; almost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Just</qex> at the point of death.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Barely; merely; scarcely; only; by a very small
space or time; <as>as, he <ex>just</ex> missed the train; <ex>just</ex>
too late.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A soft Etesian gale⟦br⟧
But <qex>just</qex> inspired and gently swelled the sail.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Just now</b></col>, <cd>the least possible time since; a
moment ago.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Just</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Just
<hw>Just</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Joust</er>.]</ety> <def>To
joust.</def> <rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Just</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Just
<hw>Just</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A joust.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Justice</ent>⟦br⟧
